@node "ScreenProje"  
   
   @{b}The Project Window@{ub}

The Project Window consists of several components, such as:
  
@{"The Window Border" Link "ProjWinBorder"} - where the projects name and the current layer will be displayed, and where you can resize and move the window as a normal Intuition window.

@{"The Coordinates and Snap Bar" Link "ProjWinCoordSnapBar"} - where you can see the current coordinate, the angle, and select different types of snaps to be applied to the input points.

@{"The Drawing Field" Link "ProjWinField"} - where the projects elements will be shown.

@{"The Text Information Bar" Link "ProjWinTextBar"} - where text information about tools is displayed.
@endnode

@node "ProjWinBorder"

   @{b}The Project Window Border@{ub}

The border of the project window contains the name of the current project, the current working layer, and scrollers used to move the current view. There are two scrollers, one for vertical and one for horizontal movement.
@endnode

@node "ProjWinCoordSnapBar"

   @{b}The Project Window Coordinates and Snap bar@{ub}

The coordinates and snap bar contains information about the current input point and the tools to affect the input points.
  
  
Coordinate Gadgets: @{u}X@{uu} @{u}Y@{uu}

The coordinate gadgets shows the coordinates of the current position on screen. This will be absolute values, except when in the middle of a drawing operation, when the coordinates will be relative to the first input point. 

The user can also type in values in these gadgets, instead of using the mouse to select points.

When the gadget shows relative values (in the middle of a drawing operation), the prefix 'a' can be used to enter an absolute value, like 'a100.00'.


Angle Gadget: @{u}Angle@{uu}

The angle gadget shows the current angle. This angle will be measured from the rightmost end of a circle, except when in the middle of some drawing operations, when it will be measured from the line between the first and second input point.
  
  
Snap gadgets: @{u}Ortho@{uu} @{u}Grid@{uu} @{u}Point@{uu} @{u}Midpoint@{uu} @{u}Endpoint@{uu}

The snap modes determine how the input points will be selected. The modes are divided into three groups, called Grid Snap, Directional Snap and Object Snap. 
@endnode

@node "ProjWinField"

   @{b}The Project Window Drawing Field@{ub}

The drawing field is where you build up your project or drawing. The current drawing mode is selected and shown in the Tools Palette.

The current coordinate is shown and the snap mode is selected in the Coordinates and Snap Bar.
@endnode

@node "ProjWinTextBar"

   @{b}The Project Window Text Information Bar@{ub}
      
The Text Information Bar will show instructions about which tool that is active, and what operation the next mouseclick will perform.

When the 'Pick' Tool is selected, it will also show how many elements that is currently selected.
@endnode

@node "TypesModif"

   @{b}The drawing modifiers@{ub}

The modifier groups occupy one row in the tools palette each.


@{u}The Element Generation Modifiers@{uu}

These modifiers occupy the first row of the tools palette. They determine which type of element the drawing operators will generate. The two types are @{"Line mode" Link "Tool_LineMode"} and @{"Enclosure Mode" Link "Tool_EnclosureMode"}.


@{u}The Topological levels@{ub}
        
The topological levels are on the 7th and 8th row of the tools palette. They determine what topological level to work at, i.e. element, segment or point. All transformations done to the selected elements, segments or points are affected by the topological levels.


@{u}The Self/Copy Modifiers@{ub}

These modifiers occupy the tenth row of the tools palette. They determine whether geometric transformations will be applied to the original object (@{"Self" Link "Tool_Self"}) or a copy of the object (@{"Copy" Link "Tool_Copy"}).
@endnode

@node "TypesOpera"

   @{b}The drawing operators@{ub}

The second group in the tools palette contains the drawing tools. These generate line or enclosure elements, depending on the active element generation modifier.


Draw Polyline

These tools draw open or closed polylines. This may be @{"polylines" Link "Tool_Polyline"} or @{"polycurves" Link "Tool_Polycurve"}.


Draw Polygon

These tools draw polygons. This may be @{"rectangle" Link "Tool_Rectangle"}, @{"3-point rectangles" Link "Tool_Rectangle3"} or @{"n-sided polygons" Link "Tool_Polygon"}.


Draw Arc

These tools draws open or closed arcs. This may be @{"arcs" Link "Tool_Arc"}, @{"circles" Link "Tool_Circle"} or @{"ellipses" Link "Tool_Ellipse"}.


Pick

This tool is used to select elements. It allows elements to be prepicked, so that an operation may be applied to an element afterwards.


Delete

This tool is used to delete elements.


Geometric Transformations

These tools is used to apply geometric transformations to elements. The available transformations are move and rotate. They operate either on the selected elements or copies of these. This is determined by current state of the Self/Copy modifiers.


Attribute Assignment

These tools are used to assign attributes to drawn elements. The available attributes are color, line style, line weight, hatch and layer.
@endnode

@node "Tool_LineMode"

   @{b}Line Mode Tool@{ub}

When Line Mode is selected, all elements will be generated with simple lines making up the element.
@endnode

@node "Tool_EnclosureMode"

   @{b}Enclosure Mode Tool@{ub}

When Enclosure Mode is selected, all elements will be generated with two parallell lines all the time, making a kind of enclosure.

This is very useful for drawing walls etc.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Polyline"

   @{b}Polyline Tool@{ub}

It draws a sequence of lines, linked to each other, by selecting a sequence of points. After the first point is selected, the first line segment will be rubberbanded. The next selected point will end the first segment and begin rubberbanding another.

The sequence is terminated by double-clicking the mouse.

Double-clicking to end the polyline will draw an open shape, with the endpoint where you double-clicked the mouse. You can hold down either of the shift keys on your keyboard while double-clicking to make a closed shape.

The point where you double-clicked will then be joined to the starting point of the polyline, closing the shape. 
@endnode

@node "Tool_Polycurve"

   @{b}Polycurve Tool@{ub}

This tool is used to draw curved lines. It is used just like the Polyline tool, except that the line drawn is a smooth curve through the points defined.

The Polycurve can not be closed like the polyline.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Arc"

   @{b}Clockwise Arcs Tool@{ub}

It draws an arc using three input points. The first point is the center of the arc. The second point defines the start point and the thrid defines the end point of the arc.

A circle will be rubberbanded when you have selected the center, and it will change to an arc when you select the start point.

The number of segments the arc consists of, can be changed in the @{"Circle/Ellipse/Arc Options requester" Link "Req_CEAOptions"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_CounterArc"

   @{b}Counter-clockwise Arc Tool@{ub}

The counter-clockwise arcs is drawn as the clockwise arcs, except that they are drawn in counter-clockwise direction.

The number of segments the arc consists of, can be changed in the @{"Circle/Ellipse/Arc Options requester" Link "Req_CEAOptions"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Circle"

   @{b}Circle Tool@{ub}

It draws a circle from two input points. The first point is the center, and the second point is the radius. The circle is rubberbanded after you have selected the center point.

The number of segments the circle consists of, can be changed in the @{"Circle/Ellipse/Arc Options requester" Link "Req_CEAOptions"}.
@endnode

@node "Req_CEAOptions"

   @{b}The Circle/Ellipse/Arc Options Requester@{ub}

This requester handles the options for the circle, ellipse and arc tools.
  
@{u}# Of Segments@{uu} - The number of segments required can be entered in this numeric field. The number must be greater than 6. The default number of sides is 48.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Ellipse"

   @{b}Ellipse Tool@{ub}

It draws an ellipse from two input points. The first point is the center, and the second point is any point on the circumference of the ellipse. After the center point is selected, the ellipse is rubber-banded.  

The number of segments the ellipse consists of, can be changed in the @{"Circle/Ellipse/Arc Options requester" Link "Req_CEAOptions"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Rectangle"

   @{b}Rectangle Tool@{ub}

It draws a rectangle from two input points that represents two diagonally opposite corners of the rectangle. After the first point is selected, the rectangle will be rubber banded until you select the second point.

The input points can be any pair of opposite corners of the rectangle. The rectangle may be a square or a plain rectangle.

The sides of the rectangle are restricted to being parallell with the x and y axes of the coordinate system.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Rectangle3"

   @{b}3 Point Rectangle Tool@{ub}

It draws a rectangle from three input points. The first point is represents one corner of the rectangle, the second determines the angle of one of the rectangle sides, and he third is the corner point opposite of the first.

The rectangle will be rubber-banded after selecting the first 2 points.

The rectangle may be a square or a plain rectangle.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Polygon"

   @{b}Polygon Tool@{ub}

It draws a polygon from two input points. These points represent the center og the polygon and the radius of the circle the polygon is inscribed in.

When you select the center point, the polygon will be rubber banded until you select the radius and direction. By default this tool creates a hexagonal shape.

The number of sides the created polygon will have can be changed in the @{"Polygon Options requester" Link "Req_PolyOptions"}. You invoke this requester by holding down either of the shift keys while selecting this tool. 
@endnode

@node "Req_PolyOptions"

   @{b}The Polygon Options Requester@{ub}

This requester handles the options for the polygon tool.
  
@{u}# Of Segments@{uu} - The number of sides required can be entered in this numeric field. The number must be greater than 2. The default number of sides is 6. 
@endnode

@node "Tool_Line"

   @{b}Line Tool@{ub}

With the Line Tool you can draw simple lines. They are defined by two points.

@endnode

@node "Tool_Point"

   @{b}Point Tool@{ub}

With the Point Tool, you can draw guiding points. A point will be placed for each mouseclick.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Text"

   @{b}Text Tool@{ub}

The Text Tool draws text. You specify one input point, which is the start position of the text. When selected, a requester will pop up and let you type the text. Press Return and OK in the requester, and the text will be displayed.

The Text can be moved and copied as other elements, but not rotated. It will always be drawn parallell with the x-axis.

The Font and String can be changed in @{"Entity Info requester" Link "Req_EntityInfo"}.
@endnode


@node "TopoLevel"

   @{b}Topological levels@{ub}

Topological levels are used for editing or erasing parts of an element. All transformations done to an element is affected by the current topological level.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Element"

   @{b}The Element Level Tool@{ub}

At element level, all operations work on the whole element. When picking, the whole element is picked, and when transforming, the whole element is transformed.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Segment"

   @{b}The Segment level Tool@{ub}

At segment level, all operations work on a segment, or more specifically a line, of the element.
@endnode

@node "Tool_LPoint"

   @{b}The Point level Tool@{ub}

At point level, all operations work on a point in the element.
@endnode

@node "PickiPrepi"

   @{b}Prepick and Postpick@{ub}

An object may be prepicked or postpicked. Using Prepick, select the object (using the Pick Tool) first, and then apply the operation. With Postpick, you can select an operation, and then pick the objects to be affected. 
@endnode

@node "Tool_Pick"

   @{b}Pick Tool@{ub}

The Pick Tool allows you to select elements on screen by various methods.

You can select one or more elements with this tool.

· Clicking on any part of an element selects it.  
· Clicking on any part of an entity, while holding down the SHIFT key, selects this in addition to any already selected elements.
· Clicking outside any element deselects all elements.
· Clicking and holding down the left mouse button while dragging the mouse produces a rectangle. All elements within this selection rectangle will be selected when yourelease the button.  

When an element is selected, it is higlighted in the current selection color.
@endnode

@node "PickiUnpic"

   @{b}Unpicking@{ub}

To unpick or deselect objects, click outside any objects in the project window while in Pick Mode.

Selecting a new topological level also unpicks all selected elements.
@endnode


@node "Tool_Delete"

   @{b}Delete Tool@{ub}

This tool deletes the selected element or elements.  

It works with both the prepick and postpick methods. With the postpick method, the Delete Tool is selected first, and then the entities are selected and deleted.

With the prepick method, all the elements are selected first, and when the Delete Tool is selected, all selected elements are deleted. Selected elements can also be deleted by pressing the 'Del' button on the keyboard.
@endnode			

@node "GeomeModif"

   @{b}The Self/Copy Modifiers@{ub}

The Self/Copy modifiers control whether the transformations are applied to the selected object or to a copy of it.

   @{"Self" Link "Tool_Self"}
   @{"Copy" Link "Tool_Copy"}
@endnode

@node "Tool_Self"
   
   @{b}Self Mode@{ub}

When the Self mode is active, all geometric transformations will be applied to the selected element.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Copy"

   @{b}Copy Mode@{ub}

When the Copy mode is active, all geometric transformations will be applied to a copy of the selected element.

A new copy of the selected element is made for each subsequent mouse click.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Explode"

   @{b}Explode Tool@{ub}
        
The Explode Tool is used to transform elements from one type to another, simpler one.

POLYCURVE,RECTANGLES,POLYFORM,CIRCLE,ELLIPSE,ARC

            will be exploded into
            
                  POLYLINE
          
          which will be exploded into
          
                    LINE


SYMBOLS will be exploded into their separate
elements.
@endnode

@node "GeomeTrans"

   @{b}The Geometric Transformation Tools@{ub}

The Geometric Transformation Tools are used to transform or change already drawn entities.

   @{"Move" Link "Tool_Move"}
   @{"Rotate" Link "Tool_Rotate"}
   @{"Scale" Link "Tool_Scale"}
   @{"Mirror" Link "Tool_Mirror"}
@endnode

@node "Tool_Move"

   @{b}Move Tool@{ub}

The Move Tool allows you to move one or more entities. The entities must be pre-picked with the pick tool.

To move the selected entities, select a point as your reference. This point can be anywhere, but preferably it is one of the entities points. When this point is selected, you can drag the entity or entities to the destination point and click to move.
@endnode

@node "Tool_Rotate"

   @{b}Rotate Tool@{ub}

The Rotate Tool allows you to rotate one or more entities. The entities must be pre-picked with the pick tool.

To rotate the selected entities, select a point as your reference. The entities will be rotated around this point. When selected, you can drag the entities to their new positions and click to end the operation.
@endnode


@node "Tool_Scale"
   
   @{b}Scale Tool@{ub}

The scale tool lets you scale the elements, making them bigger or smaller. The elements must be pre-picked using the Pick tool.

To scale a selected element, select one point as the point to scale from (a fixed point). Then drag out a line to use as 100%, and select a new point. The element will now be rubberbanded and is scaled according to your movement of the mouse. Click once when the right scale is shown. 
@endnode

@node "Tool_Mirror"

   @{b}Mirror Tool@{ub}

The mirror tool lets you mirror an element around a line. The element must be pre-picked using the Pick tool.

You must select two points, defining a line in the direction you want the element to be mirrored. It will be mirrored around a line at a 90 degree angle to the line you define.

When you have selected the two points, the element will be rubberbanded, following your mouse movements. Click once to mirror the element when it is in the right position.

THIS TOOL IS NOT SUPPORTED IN THIS VERSION
@endnode

@node "GeomeObjec"

   @{b}Transforming Objects@{ub}

All elements support both the transformations above, except the Text and Symbol elements. These can only be moved, not rotated. If a rotation is applied to a Text element, only the starting point of the Text will be rotated/moved.
@endnode

@node "ElemeSetti"

   @{b}Setting the element attributes@{ub}

When new elements are drawn, they will have the attributes currently set. These attributes are color, line style and line weight. They will also be placed in the currently active layer. 

The hatch attribute must be set explicitly. 

After an element has been drawn, these attributes may be changed by using the attribute setting tools, found at the bottom of the Tools Palette.

   @{"Set Color" Link "Tool_SetColor"}
   @{"Set Hatch" Link "Tool_SetHatch"}
   @{"Set Line Style" Link "Tool_SetLineStyle"}
   @{"Set Line Weight" Link "Tool_SetLineWeight"}
   @{"Set Layer" Link "Tool_SetLayer"}
   @{"Set All" Link "Tool_SetAll"}
@endnode

@node "Tool_SetColor"
   
   @{b}Set Color Tool@{ub}

This tool changes the color of the selected element to the current selected color.

The currently selected color can be changed by selecting a new color in the @{"Color Palette" Link "Req_Color"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SetLineStyle"

   @{b}Set Line Style Tool@{ub}

This tool changes the line style of the selected element to the current selected line style.

The currently selected line style can be changed in the @{"Line Menu" Link "Menu_Line"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SetLineWeight"

   @{b}Set Line Weight Tool@{ub}

This tool changes the line weight (or line width) of the selected element to the current selected line weight.

The currently selected line weight can be changed in the Line Menu.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SetHatch"

   @{b}Set Hatch Tool@{ub}

This tool allows you to hatch elements on screen by selecting them by the same methods as in Pick.

The elements will be hatched with the currently selected hatch type, which can be selected in the @{"Hatch Palette" Link "Req_Hatch"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SetLayer"

   @{b}Set Layer Tool@{ub}

This tool lets you change the layer of the selected element to the current layer.

The current layer can be changed in the @{"Layers requester" Link "Req_Layers"}.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SetAll"

   @{b}Set All Tool@{ub}

This tool lets you change all the attributes of an element.

This means that the Color, Line Style, Line Weight, Hatch and Layer of the entity will be set to the current values. 
@endnode

@node "Tool_CreateSymbol"

   @{b}Create Symbol Tool@{ub}

This creates a symbol from the currently selected entities. This tool works only with prepicked elements.

The symbol will be saved in a symbol file with the name the user supplies.
@endnode

@node "Tool_PlaceSymbol"

   @{b}Place Symbol Tool@{ub}

This tool is used to place a symbol in a project. A requester appears and lets the user select the appropriate symbol. This symbol is loaded and the user may move it around and place it in the project window.
@endnode

@node "Tool_GridSnap"}

   @{b}Grid Snap Switch@{ub}

Toggles the grid snap mode on and off. When Grid Snap mode is on, snapping occurs to the closest point on the reference grid, as defined in the Grid Settings requester.

Note that this mode may be overruled by the directional or object snap modes, when the pointer is near one of these points.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SnapOrtho"

   @{b}Orthogonal@{ub}

When orthogonal snapping is active, snapping occurs to a line parallell with either the x or y axis,
or to a line 45 degrees to this. 

Note that the directional snap modes may be overruled by the object snap modes.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SnapPoint"

   @{b}Point@{ub}

When snap to point is active, snapping occurs to the closest point which is in an element, if the pointer is near enough to such a point.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SnapMidPoint"

   @{b}Midpoint@{ub}

When snap to midpoint is active, snapping occurs to the closest midpoint which is on a line in an element.

This mode will also snap to the center of circles, ellipses and arcs.

Note that the object snap modes overrules all other snap modes.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SnapEndPoint"

   @{b}Endpoint Snap Tool@{ub}

@endnode

@node "Tool_SnapCenterPoint"

   @{b}Centerpoint Snap Tool@{ub}

This tool is used to snap to the center of elements.
@endnode

@node "Tool_SnapCrossing"

   @{b}Snap Crossing Tool@{ub}

This tool is used to snap to the intersection of two elements elements.
@endnode

@node "SecMenus" "Menus"

   @{b}The Menus@{ub}

From the menus the user can access all the functions not covered in the tools palette.


   @{"Project Menu" Link "MenusProje"}
   @{"Edit Menu" Link "MenusEdit"}
   @{"View Menu" Link "MenusView"}
   @{"Arrange Menu" Link "MenusInfor"}
   @{"ARexx Menu" Link "Menu_ARexx"}
   @{"Settings Menu" Link "MenusSetti"}
   @{"Lines Menu" Link "MenusLines"}
   @{"Help Menu" Link "MenusHelp"}
@endnode


@node "MenusProje" "Menu: Project"

   @{b}Project Menu@{ub}

The Project Menu contains everything that has to do with opening and closing projects and files.

   @{"New" Link "MenuProjNew"}
   @{"New Window" Link "MenuProjNewWindow"}

   @{"Open..." Link "MenuProjOpen"}
   @{"Close" Link "MenuProjClose"}
   @{"Save" Link "MenuProjSave"}
   @{"Save As..." Link "MenuProjSaveas"}

   @{"Print Setup..." Link "MenuProjPrintSetup"}
   @{"Print" Link "MenuProjPrint"}

   @{"About" Link "MenuProjAbout"}

   @{"Quit" Link "MenuProjQuit"}
@endnode

@node "MenuProjNew" "Menu: Project/New"

   @{b}New@{ub}

This opens a new project. If the current open project is changed, you will be asked if you want to save before opening a new project. 

Preferences will be read from the current preferences file.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjNewWindow" "Menu: Project/New Window"

   @{b}New Window@{ub}

This opens a new window unto the current project.  

NOT AVAILABLE IN THE CURRENT VERSION.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjOpen" "Menu: Project/Open..."

   @{b}Open...@{ub}

This displays the filerequester and lets the user select a new project to load.

If the current open project is changed, you will be asked if you want to save before opening a new project.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjClose" "Menu: Project/Close"

   @{b}Close@{ub}

Closes the current project.

If the current open project is changed, you will be asked if you want to save before opening a new project.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjSave" "Menu: Project/Save"

   @{b}Save@{ub}

Saves the current project with the current filename.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjSaveas" "Menu: Project/Save as"

   @{b}Save as@{ub}

Opens a save requester and allows you to type in a new name for this project, and saves it under this name.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjPrintSetup" "Menu: Project/Print Setup"

   @{b}Print Setup...@{ub}

Displays the @{"Print Setup requester" Link "Req_Print"} and lets you print the current project. 
@endnode

@node "Req_Print" "Requester: Print Setup"

   @{b}The Print Setup Requester@{ub}
      
This requester lets you change the print setup settings.
  
@{u}Print Scale@{uu} - The scale of the printed drawing.
@{u}Print Method@{uu}
           - Normal: Print using graphics dump routines.
           - PostScript: Print using PostScript. When the
             'PostScript' method is selected, the
             'PostScript Setup...' gadget will be available
             to set the PostScript settings.
@{u}Print Direction@{uu} - Sets the printing to either Landscape or Portrait.
@{u}Print Type@{uu} - Determines what part of the project that is to be printed. If Extents, everything will be printed. If Current View, the part of the project that is shown in the project window will be printed.
  
Options:
@{u}Print Grid@{uu} - If checked, print the reference grid.
@{u}Print Axis@{uu} - If checked, print the reference axis.
@{u}Print Border@{uu} - If checked, a thin border will be printed around each page when printing.

@{u}Preview@{uu} - Show a preview of the printout.
@{u}PostScript...@{uu} - Show the @{"'PostScript Setup'" Link "Req_PostScript"} requester.

@{u}OK@{uu} - Close the requester and make changes.
@{u}Print@{uu} - Print with the current options.
@{u}Cancel@{uu} - Close the requester, reset parameters as before.
@endnode

@node "Req_PostScript" "Requester: PostScript Setup"

   @{b}The PostScript Setup Requester@{ub}
      
This requester lets you change the PostScript setup.

Destination:

@{u}Destination@{uu}
           - Printer: Print directly to an attached printer.
             Both the 'PAR:' and 'SER:' devices are supported
             for printer connection. 
           - File: Print to a PostScript file. This allows you
             to bring the .ps file produced to another computer
             to print it out.
             
@{u}Output to@{uu} 
           - If 'Destination' is set to 'printer', you can
             select the device to output to here (either
             'PAR:' or 'SER:').
           - If 'Destination' is set to 'file', you can
             select the file name of the PostScript file
             by entering the name or pressing the 'Select...'
             button to find a file name.

Options:
                     
@{u}Horizontal Offset@{uu} - The horizontal offset of the printout.
@{u}Vertical Offset@{uu} - The vertical offset of the printout.
@{u}Horizontal Scale@{uu} - The horizontal scaling of the printout.
@{u}Vertical Scale@{uu} - The vertical scaling of the printout.
@{u}Rotate by@{uu} - Rotation factor for the printout.

@{u}OK@{uu} - Close the requester and make changes.
@{u}Cancel@{uu} - Close the requester, reset parameters as before.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjPrint" "Menu: Project/Print"

   @{b}Print@{ub}

Prints the current project with the selections set in the @{"Print Setup requester" Link "Req_Print"}. 
@endnode

@node "MenuProjAbout" "Menu: Project/About"

   @{b}About@{ub}

This displays the 'About' requester, where you can see the program credits and information about how much memory that is available.

The name of the public screen used and the name of the ARexx Port will also be displayed.
@endnode

@node "MenuProjQuit" "Menu: Project/Quit"

   @{b}Quit@{ub}

This quits MagnifiCAD.

If the current open project is changed, you will be asked if you want to save before the program ends.
@endnode

@node "MenusEdit" "Menu: Edit"

   @{b}Edit Menu@{ub}

The items in the Edit Menu lets you cut and paste elements in a project and between different projects. It also has an item for selecting all elements in a project.

   @{"Cut" Link "MenuEditCut"}
   @{"Copy" Link "MenuEditCopy"}
   @{"Paste" Link "MenuEditPaste"}
   @{"Select All" Link "MenuEditSelectAll"}
@endnode

@node "MenuEditCut" "Menu: Edit/Cut"

   @{b}Cut@{ub}

This deletes the selected elements from the project and stores them in the clipboard, ready for a @{"Paste" Link "MenuEditPaste"} operation. The clipboard can hold any number of elements.

If there are old elements in the clipboard (from another Cut or Copy operation), they will be replaced by the new elements.
@endnode

@node "MenuEditCopy" "Menu: Edit/Copy"

   @{b}Copy@{ub}

This copies the selected elements into the clipboard, replacing anything already there. It is the same as @{"Cut" Link "MenuEditCut"}, except it does not delete the elements from the project.
@endnode

@node "MenuEditPaste" "Menu: Edit/Paste"

   @{b}Paste@{ub}

This pastes a copy of the elements in the clipboard into the project. The elements to be copied will be follow the position of the mouse until the mouse is clicked to position them.

The elements will not be removed from the clipboard, so the Paste command can be used many times to paste many copies of the same elements into the project. 

The contents of the clipboard will not be deleted when closing a project and opening a new one, so it can be used for copying elements from one project to another.
@endnode

@node "MenuEditSelectAll" "Menu: Edit/Select All"

   @{b}Select All@{ub}

This selects all the elements in a project. Elements in a layer that is not shown will not be selected.
@endnode

@node "MenusView" "Menu: View"

   @{b}View Menu@{b}

The items in the view menu lets you change the view you have of the project, zoom in and out, and save a specific view for later.

   @{"Zoom In" Link "Menu_ZoomIn"}
   @{"Zoom In By Factor" Link "Menu_ZoomInByFactor"}
   @{"Zoom All" Link "Menu_ZoomAll"}
   @{"Zoom Out By Factor" Link "Menu_ZoomOutByFactor"}
   @{"Pan" Link "Menu_Pan"}
         
   @{"Redraw" Link "Menu_Redraw"}
      
   @{"Save View" Link "Menu_SaveView"}
   @{"Views..." Link "Menu_Views"}
      
   @{"Coordinates and Snap Bar" Link "Menu_CoordinatesAndSnapBar"}
   @{"Text Information Bar" Link "Menu_TextInformationBar"}
   @{"Tools Palette" Link "Menu_ToolsPalette"}
   @{"Color	Palette" Link "Menu_ColorPalette"}
   @{"Hatch Palette" Link "Menu_HatchPalette"}
@endnode

@node "Menu_ZoomIn" "Menu: View/Zoom In"

   @{b}Zoom In@{ub}

This lets you zoom in by drawing a rectangle which defines the bounds of the zoom.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ZoomInByFactor" "Menu: View/Zoom In By Factor"

   @{b}Zoom In By Factor@{ub}

This calculates a new view based on the values in the Zoom Settings requester.

It zooms in by the number set in the Zoom Factor gadget in the @{"Zoom Settings requester" Link "Req_Zoom"}.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ZoomAll" "Menu: View/Zoom All"

   @{b}Zoom All@{ub}

This zooms out to show the whole current working area.

The working area can be set in the 'Size' requester, available from the 'Arrange' menu.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ZoomOutByFactor" "Menu: View/Zoom Out By Factor"

   @{b}Zoom Out By Factor@{ub}

This calculates a new view based on the values in the @{"Zoom Settings requester" Link "Req_Zoom"}.

It zooms out by the number set in the Zoom Factor gadget in the Zoom Settings requester.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Pan" "Menu: View/Pan"

   @{b}Pan@{ub}

This lets you move the current view by drawing a line with the length and direction that the view moves.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Redraw" "Menu: View/Redraw"

   @{b}Redraw@{ub}

This redraws the project with the current view. 
@endnode

@node "Menu_SaveView" "Menu: View/Save view"

   @{b}Save View@{ub}

This lets you type in a name for the current view and saves it in the view list.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Views" "Menu: View/Views"

   @{b}Views...@{ub}

Shows the view list and lets you select a new view.
@endnode

@node "Menu_CoordinatesAndSnapBar" "Menu: View/Coordinates and Snap Bar"

   @{b}Coordinates and Snap Bar@{ub}

Show or hide the Coordinates and Snap Bar. When the Coordinates and Snap Bar is shown, this item will be marked.
@endnode

@node "Menu_TextInformationBar" "Menu: View/Text Information Bar"

   @{b}Text Information Bar@{ub}
 
Show or hide the Text Information Bar. When the Text Information Bar is shown, this item will be marked.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ToolsPalette" "Menu: View/Tools Palette"

   @{b}Tools Palette@{ub}

Show or hide the Tools Palette. When the Tools Palette is shown, this item will be marked.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ColorPalette" "Menu: View/Color Palette"

   @{b}Color Palette@{ub}

Show or hide the @{"Color Palette" Link "Req_Color"}. When the Color Palette is shown, this item will be marked.

@node "Req_Color" "Requester: Color Palette"

   @{b}Color Palette@{ub}

This requester lets you select the current color. Select a color to make it the current selected color.
@endnode

@node "Menu_HatchPalette" "Menu: View/Hatch Palette"

   @{b}Hatch Palette@{ub}

Show or hide the @{"Hatch Palette" Link "Req_Hatch"}. When the Hatch Palette is shown, this item will be marked.

@node "Req_Hatch" "Requester: Hatch Palette"

   @{b}Hatch Palette@{ub}

This requester lets you select the current hatch. There are 16 different hatches available, from plain solid to a brick-like hatch.

Select the one you require by clicking on it. It will be depressed to show that it is selected.
@endnode

@node "MenusInfor" "Menu: Arrange"

   @{b}Arrange Menu@{ub}

The Arrange Menu contains items that shows the user information about the project, its layers, and its elements, and commands to arrange the elements.

   @{"Project..." Link "Menu_Project"}
   @{"Size..." Link "Menu_Size"}

   @{"Layers..." Link "Menu_Layers"}

   @{"Element Info..." Link "Menu_EntityInfo"}
   @{"Group" Link "Menu_Group"}
   @{"Ungroup" Link "Menu_Ungroup"}
   @{"Move to front" Link "Menu_MoveToFront"}
   @{"Move to back" Link "Menu_MoveToBack"}
@endnode


@node "Menu_Project" "Menu: Arrange/Project..."

   @{b}Project...@{ub}

This displays the @{"Project requester" Link "Req_Project"}. In this requester you can change the name of the project and the file type.
@endnode


@node "Req_Project" "Requester: Project"

   @{b}The Project Requester@{ub}

This requester lets you change the project name and file type.
  
@{u}Name@{uu} - The project's name.
@{u}File Type@{uu} - The file type the project is saved in. The file types currently supported are:
          MagnifiCAD
          @{"AutoCAD DXF 2D" Link "AppUsiAutoc"}

For more information about these filetypes, see Appendix A.

@{u}Creation Date@{uu} - the creation date of the project will be shown here. This can not be edited.

@{u}Calculate Statistics@{uu} - the statistics for the project (number of elements, segments and points) will be calculated when clicking this gadget.
@endnode


@node "Menu_Size" "Menu: Arrange/Size..."

   @{b}Size...@{ub}

This displays the @{"Size Requester" Link "Req_Size"}. In this requester, the user may set the current work-area size for the project, or have it calculated.
@endnode


@node "Req_Size" "Requester: Size"

   @{b}The Size Requester@{ub}

This requester lets the user change the current
work-area size, or have it calculated.

@{u}X min@{uu}     - Starting X coordinate of the
                     work-area.
@{u}X max@{uu}     - Ending X coordinate of the
                     work-area.
@{u}Y min@{uu}     - Starting Y coordinate of the
                     work-area.
@{u}Y max@{uu}     - Ending Y coordinate of the
                     work-area.

@{u}OK@{uu}        - Accept the changes made.
@{u}Calculate@{uu} - Calculate the current work-area,
                     making the area 5% bigger than a
                     rectangle that encloses all the
                     elements.
@{u}Cancel@{uu}    - Abort this requester, leaving
                     things as they were.
@endnode
        

@node "Menu_Layers" "Menu: Arrange/Layers..."

   @{b}Layers...@{ub}

This displays the @{"Layers requester" Link "Req_Layers"}. In this requester you can change number, name and status for each layer.

You change the active layer by clicking in the list of layers.
@endnode


@node "Req_Layers" "Requester: Layers"

   @{b}The Layers Requester@{ub}

This requester shows the layer list of the current project. You can add or delete layers, and change layer attributes.

Layer List:
@{u}Add@{uu}    - Add a new layer to the layer list.
@{u}Delete@{uu} - Delete the currently selected layer.
     
Current Layer:
@{u}Number@{uu} - The layers number.
@{u}Name@{uu}   - The layers name.
@{u}State@{uu}  - The layers state, either Show or Hide. When Show is selected, the layer's entities will be drawn.
@endnode

@node "Menu_EntityInfo" "Menu: Arrange/Element Info..."

   @{b}Element Info...@{ub}

This displays the @{"Element Information requester" Link "Req_Entities"}, which shows information about the selected entity. You can change information from this Entity Info requester.

If there is more than one entity selected, selecting this item will do nothing.
@endnode

@node "Req_Entities" "Requester: Element Information"

   @{b}The Element Info Requester@{ub}

This requester shows some information about the selected element(s).
  
All entities:
@{u}Type@{uu} - This shows the entity type. This can not be changed.
@{u}Layer@{uu} - This shows the current layer the element is drawn in. Type in a new existing layer number to change the element's layer.
@{u}X position@{uu} - The X position of the element. If this is changed, the whole element is moved.
@{u}Y position@{uu} - The Y position of the element. If this is changed, the whole element will be moved.

Additional information for specific element types:

Line:
@{u}Length@{uu} - The length of this line element.
@{u}Angle@{uu} - The angle of this line element.

Polyform:
@{u}# of sides@{uu} - The number of sides for this polyform.

Circle:
@{u}Radius@{uu} - The radius of the circle.

Ellipse:
@{u}X radius@{uu} - The radius in the X direction.
@{u}Y radius@{uu} - The radius in the Y direction.

Arc:
@{u}Radius@{uu} - The radius of the arc.
@{u}Start angle@{uu} - The start angle of the arc.
@{u}End angle@{uu} - The end angle of the arc.

Text:
@{u}Text@{uu} - The text that is drawn. This can be changed by editing the string.
@{u}Height@{uu} - The height (or scaling) of this text element.
@{u}Font@{uu} - The font set for this element.
@{u}Select...@{uu} - Select a new font to use for this text element. The font will be selected from the fonts requester.

Group:
@{u}# of elements@{uu} - The number of elements contained in the group.    

Symbol:
@{u}Scaling@{uu} - The scaling factor of the symbol (set to 1.0 when placing a new symbol).
@{u}Rotation@{uu} - The rotation of the symbol in degrees. This is set to 0 for all new symbols.
@{u}Symbol@{uu} - The name of symbol. This can be changed by typing a new name.
@{u}Select...@{uu} - Select a new symbol to use. This brings up a requester where you can choose another symbol.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Group" "Menu: Arrange/Group"

   @{b}Group@{ub}

The Group command can be used to group entities to treat them as one. They can be selected and manipulated as they were one element.

The 'Ungroup' command can be used to ungroup the elements.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Ungroup" "Menu: Arrange/Ungroup"

   @{b}Ungroup@{ub}

The Ungroup command can be used to ungroup entities that previously have been grouped with the 'Group' command.
@endnode

@node "Menu_MoveToBack" "Menu: Arrange/Move To Back"

   @{b}Move To Back@{ub}

The 'Move to back' command can be used to move the currently selected elements behind other elements.

The elements will be moved to the back of their layer.
@endnode

@node "Menu_MoveToFront" "Menu: Arrange/Move To Front"

   @{b}Move To Front@{ub}

The 'Move to front' command can be used to move the currently selected elements in front of other elements.

The elements will be moved to the front of their layer.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ARexx" "Menu: ARexx"

   @{b}ARexx Menu@{ub}

The items in the ARexx menu lets you set up, record and run ARexx macros/scripts.

   @{"Assign Macros..." Link "Menu_AssignMacros"}
   
   @{"Macro #0-9" Link "Menu_Macros"}
   @{"Run other macro..." Link "Menu_RunOtherMacro"}
        
   @{"ARexx Command Shell" Link "Menu_ARexxCommandShell"}
   
   @{"Start recording" Link "Menu_StartRecording"}
   @{"Stop recording" Link "Menu_Stoprecording"}
        
   @{"Load Macros..." Link "Menu_LoadMacros"}
   @{"Save Macros" Link "Menu_SaveMacros"}
   @{"Save Macros as..." Link "Menu_SaveMacrosAs"}
@endnode

@node "Menu_AssignMacros" "Menu: ARexx/Assign Macros..."

   @{b}Assign Macros...@{ub}

This command will display the @{"ARexx Macro Setup" Link "Req_Macros"} requester, allowing the user to change the macro setup.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Macros" "Menu: ARexx/Macro #0-9"

   @{b}Macro #0-9@{ub}

Selecting one of these commands runs the macro assigned to the specific number. The name of the assigned macro is shown in the menu.
@endnode

@node "Menu_RunOtherMacro" "Menu: ARexx/Run other macro..."

   @{b}Run other macro...@{ub}

Selecting this item will display a filerequester, asking the user to select the ARexx Macro to be executed.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ARexxCommandShell" "Menu: ARexx/ARexx Command Shell"

   @{b}ARexx Command Shell@{ub}

Selecting this item will open or close the ARexx Command Shell window.

In this window you can enter ARexx commands directly while working.
@endnode

@node "Menu_StartRecording" "Menu: ARexx/Start recording"

   @{b}Start recording@{ub}

Selecting this command will start recording all the operations executed, putting them into an ARexx macro.

See also 'Stop recording'.
@endnode

@node "Menu_StopRecording" "Menu: ARexx/Stop recording"

   @{b}Stop recording@{ub}

Selecting this command will stop the recording of ARexx commands and prompt the user for a filename to save the recorded macro under.
@endnode

@node "Menu_LoadMacros" "Menu: ARexx/Load Macros..."

   @{b}Load Macros...@{ub}

This command will display a filerequester, allowing the user to select a macro setup file to load.
@endnode

@node "Menu_SaveMacros" "Menu: ARexx/Save Macros"

   @{b}Save Macros@{ub}

Selecting this command will save the current macro setup under the current macro setup name.
@endnode

@node "Menu_SaveMacrosAs" "Menu: ARexx/Save Macros As..."

   @{b}Save Macros as...@{ub}

This command will display a filerequester, allowing the user to select a name to save the current macro setup under.
@endnode

@node "MenusSetti" "Menu: Settings"

   @{b}Settings Menu@{ub}

The items in the settings menu lets you change all the settings in MagnifiCAD, and save this in a preference file.

   @{"Show Grid" Link "Menu_ShowGrid"}
   @{"Create Icons?" Link "Menu_CreateIcons"}
   @{"Workbench" Link "Menu_Workbench"}

   @{"Screen..." Link "Menu_Screen"}
   @{"Colors..." Link "Menu_Colors"}
   @{"Grid..." Link "Menu_Grid"}
   @{"Pick..." Link "Menu_Pick"}
   @{"Units..." Link "Menu_Units"}
   @{"Zoom..." Link "Menu_Zoom"}

   @{"Load Settings..." Link "Menu_LoadSettings"}
   @{"Save Settings" Link "Menu_SaveSettings"}
   @{"Save Settings As..." Link "SaveSettingsAs"}
@endnode

@node "Menu_ShowGrid"

   @{b}Show Grid@{ub}

Selecting this item will toggle it on or off. When on, the grid, as defined in the Grid Settings requester, will be displayed.
@endnode

@node "Menu_CreateIcons"

   @{b}Create Icons@{ub}
        
Selecting this item will toggle it on or off. When on, an icon of the appropriate type will be created for each file you save.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Workbench"

   @{b}Workbench@{ub}

Select this item to Open or Close the Workbench screen.

The state of the Workbench Screen will be reflected in the checkmark. The Workbench will not always be closed when selecting this item, therefore it will not always seem to do anything.

The Workbench Screen can be closed to save memory.

Be aware that selecting Workbench/Close doesn't always mean that the Workbench screen actually will be closed.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Screen"

   @{b}Screen...@{ub}

This displays the @{"Screen Settings" Link "Req_Screen"} requester, allowing the user to change the settings of the screen.
@endnode

@node "Req_Screen" "Requester: Screen Settings"

   @{b}The Screen Settings Requester@{ub}

This requester shows the current screen settings.

Screen Mode:
   Select Screen Mode - Shows the @{"Screen Mode" Link "Menu_ScreenMode"} requester with the current display mode and screen size.
   Y Ratio - The current Y Ratio. This is the Y scaling for the screen mode selected. For special screen modes, the 'Y Ratio' may need adjustment to get the right on-screen ratios.
Public Screen:
   MagnifiCAD - open MagnifiCAD its own public screen named 'MagnifiCAD'.
   Workbench  - open MagnifiCAD on the Workbench screen. 
Fonts:
   Screen Text - the font used in the window and screen titles.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ScreenMode"

   @{b}Screen Mode...@{ub}

This displays the screenmode-requester and lets the user change screen resolution and depth (number of colors on screen).

The screen modes currently supported by MagnifiCAD is:

   o HIRES
   o HIRES INTERLACE
   o SUPERHIRES
   o SUPERHIRES INTERLACE

Both PAL and NTSC modes are available.

Other screen modes should also work OK with MagnifiCAD, but the Y Ratio must be set for each mode.

Colors from 16 to 256 is supported. 
@endnode

@node "Menu_Colors"

   @{b}Colors...@{ub}

This shows the @{"Color Setting Requester" Link "Req_Colors"} and lets you edit the colors.
@endnode

@node "Req_Colors"

   @{b}The Color Settings Requester@{ub}

This requester shows the color settings.

@{u}Color Wheel@{uu} - drag the knob around the edit the current color.
@{u}Color Slider@{uu} - drag the knob up (to make the color brighter) or down (to make the color darker).

@{u}Color Palette@{uu} - select a color here to make it the current color to edit.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Grid" 

   @{b}Grid...@{ub}

This shows the @{"Grid Settings requester" Link "Req_Grid"} and lets you change the grid settings.
@endnode

@node "Req_Grid" "Requester: Grid Settings"

   @{b}The Grid Settings Requester@{ub}

This requester shows the grid settings.
  
@{u}Grid Spacing@{uu} - The spacing of the points or lines in the reference grid. If the spacing equals less than 2 pixels on the screen in the current view, they will not be drawn.
@{u}Type@{uu} - When set to Dot grid, only the points in the reference grid will be drawn. When set to Line grid, continous lines will be drawn as the reference grid.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Units" "Menu: Settings/Units..."

   @{b}Units...@{ub}

This shows the @{"Units Settings requester" Link "Req_Units"} and lets you change the units settings. 
@endnode

@node "Req_Units" "Requester: Unit Settings"

   @{b}The Units Settings Requester@{ub}
      
This requester shows the Units settings.
    
@{u}Units@{uu} - The base units which all measures are made in. The base unit is used when calculating scale.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Zoom" "Menu: Settings/Zoom..."

   @{b}Zoom...@{ub}

This shows the @{"Zoom Settings requester" Link "Req_Zoom"} and lets you change the zoom settings. They affect how the view is zoomed when using one of the zoom commands.
@endnode

@node "Req_Zoom" "Requester: Zoom Settings"

   @{b}The Zoom Settings Requester@{ub}

This requester shows the zoom settings.
  
@{u}Zoom Factor@{uu} - This is the factor that is used in calculating new views when selecting Zoom In By Factor or Zoom Out By Factor.
@{u}Always Zoom By Factor@{uu} - When checked, the Zoom Factor is used in all zooming operations, i.e. Zoom All and Zoom In. These operations will then always scale by Zoom Factor.
@endnode

@node "Menu_LoadSettings" "Menu: Settings/Load Settings..."

   @{b}Load Settings...@{ub}

This lets you change the settings by loading a previously saved settings file from disk.
@endnode

@node "Menu_SaveSettings" "Menu: Settings/Save Settings"

   @{b}Save Settings@{ub}

This saves the settings in the currently defined file.
@endnode

@node "SaveSettingsAs" "Menu: Settings/Save Settings as..."

   @{b}Save Settings as...@{ub}

This saves the settings in a file with a filename selected by the user.
@endnode

@node "MenusLines" "Menu: Lines"

   @{b}Lines Menu@{ub}

In this menu you can select the current Line Style and the current Line Weight.

A selection mark will show the current Line Style and the current Line Weight.

@endnode

